Creation of the Monster Index¶

In [ ]:
#Creation of a monster index
#Computing returns and prices of our hedge found index
dates=hedge_fd.iloc[:,0]
#Getting the notmalized prices of the hedge founds
prices_hf=hedge_fd.iloc[:,1:]/hedge_fd.iloc[0,1:] #normalized prices
initial_price=hedge_fd.iloc[0,1:]

#Calculate the returns
returns = (hedge_fd.iloc[1:, 1:].values/ hedge_fd.iloc[:-1, 1:].values) - 1
returns = pd.DataFrame(returns, columns=hedge_fd.columns[1:])

#Creation of a Monster index
w_MXWO=0.25
w_LEGATRUU=0.25
w_HFRXGL=0.5

#Computing normalized prices and prices of our Monster Index
y_price=w_MXWO*hedge_fd.iloc[:,1]+w_LEGATRUU*hedge_fd.iloc[:,2]+w_HFRXGL*hedge_fd.iloc[:,3]
y_values = pd.DataFrame(y_price, columns=['Target'])
y_price=y_values/y_values.iloc[0]
#Computing returns of our monster index
returns_MI = (y_price.iloc[1:].values/ y_price.iloc[:-1].values) - 1
returns_MI = pd.DataFrame(returns_MI, columns=['Target'])
returns_MI['Target'] = pd.to_numeric(returns_MI['Target'] , errors='coerce')

#Plot
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(13, 4))

#Plot of the Normalized Prices
ax1.plot(dates,prices_hf,label=('Price MXWO', 'Price MXWD','Price LEGATRUU','Price HFRXGL'),linewidth=0.5)
ax1.plot(dates,y_price, label=('Monster index'), linewidth=4,c='b')
ax1.set_xlabel('Time Series')
ax1.set_ylabel('Normalized prices')
ax1.set_title('Normalized prices of hedge found indexes and monster index')

ax1.legend()

# Plot Monster Index returns
ax2.plot(returns_MI['Target'], label='Monster Index Returns', color='blue')
ax2.set_xlabel('Time')
ax2.set_ylabel('Returns')
ax2.set_title('Monster Index Returns')
ax2.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Data Exploration of the Monster Index¶

In this section, we explore the dataset in relation to the target variable: the Monster Index. Specifically, we examine the following statistical properties of its returns:

  • Gaussianity
  • Stationarity
  • Autocorrelation

All this analysis has been done with respect to the returns

Gaussianity

Gaussianity

In [ ]:
# GAUSSIANITY STUDY

# Function to check Gaussianity for each future
def check_gaussianity(data):
    for column in data.columns:
        # Perform Shapiro-Wilk test
        stat_sw, p_sw = shapiro(data[column])
        print(f'{column} - Shapiro-Wilk Statistic: {stat_sw}, p-value: {p_sw}')
        if p_sw > 0.05:
            print(f'The data for {column} appears to be normally distributed according to Shapiro-Wilk test.')
        else:
            print(f'The data for {column} does not appear to be normally distributed according to Shapiro-Wilk test.')

        # Perform D'Agostino's K^2 test
        stat_k2, p_k2 = normaltest(data[column])
        print(f"{column} - D'Agostino's K^2 Statistic: {stat_k2}, p-value: {p_k2}")
        if p_k2 > 0.05:
            print(f"The data for {column} appears to be normally distributed according to D'Agostino's K^2 test.")
        else:
            print(f"The data for {column} does not appear to be normally distributed according to D'Agostino's K^2 test.")

        # Plot histogram and Q-Q plot
        plt.figure(figsize=(14, 4))
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.hist(data[column], bins=20, density=True)
        plt.title(f'Histogram of {column} Returns')
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        probplot(data[column], dist='norm', plot=plt)
        plt.title(f'Q-Q Plot of {column} Returns')
        plt.show()

# Check Gaussianity of futures returns
check_gaussianity(returns_futures)

Stationarity

In [ ]:
# STATIONARITY STUDY


# Function to check stationarity for each future
def check_stationarity(data):
    for column in data.columns:
        result = adfuller(data[column])
        print(f'{column} - ADF Statistic: {result[0]}')
        print(f'{column} - p-value: {result[1]}')
        print('Critical Values:')
        for key, value in result[4].items():
            print(f'   {key}: {value}')
        if result[1] <= 0.05:
            print(f'The time series for {column} appears to be stationary (reject the null hypothesis of non-stationarity).')
        else:
            print(f'The time series for {column} does not appear to be stationary (fail to reject the null hypothesis of non-stationarity).')
        # Plot the returns to visually inspect stationarity
        plt.figure(figsize=(14, 4))
        plt.plot(data[column], label=f'{column} Returns')
        plt.title(f'Time Series of {column} Returns')
        plt.xlabel('Time')
        plt.ylabel('Returns')
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()

# Check stationarity of futures returns
check_stationarity(returns_futures)

Future Selection¶

We now concatenate our target variable (Monster Index) to the futures, in order to create a new dataset on which developing some models.

In [ ]:
# Concatenate the Target to the Futures
df_concat = pd.concat([returns_MI ,returns_futures], axis=1)

# Compute the Correlation Matrix
correlation_matrix = df_concat.corr(method='kendall')

# Corelation matrix with Heat map
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
sns.heatmap(correlation_matrix, annot=True, cmap='viridis', fmt=".2f")
plt.title('Correlation Matrix between Futures and Target')
plt.show()

We then checked for the correlation between Futures and the Target in order to understand wheter to use all the Futures or not. The idea is to use only the highly correlated Futures

In [ ]:
# Definisci il threshold di correlazione
threshold_up = 0.4
threshold_down = -0.1

# Seleziona le colonne con correlazione superiore ai threshold
highly_correlated_futures = correlation_matrix[
    (correlation_matrix['Target'] > threshold_up) |
    (correlation_matrix['Target'] < threshold_down)
]

# Ottieni solo i nomi delle colonne (future) più correlate con il target
futures_names = highly_correlated_futures.index.tolist()

# Visualizza i nomi delle futures più correlate con il target
print("Futures più correlate con il target (con correlazione maggiore di 0.4 o minore di -0.1):")
print(futures_names)

Futures più correlate con il target (con correlazione maggiore di 0.4 o minore di -0.1):
['Target', 'RX1', 'TY1', 'ES1', 'VG1', 'NQ1', 'TP1', 'DU1', 'TU2']

We also decided to get rid of the NQ1 because we can see that's highly correlated with ES1 and so in order to reduce the transaction cost we excluded it.

In [ ]:

price_futures_corr = price_futures[futures_names_new]
